  "pattern_name": "Character-pair scene density",
  "description": "Per-book ensemble-size distribution across scenes and beats; per-chapter dominant ensemble; top character-pair frequencies. Pure compute on beats.jsonl + scenes.jsonl; no LLM.",
  "rationale": "Feeds the planner's charactersPresent per-chapter prior. Currently the planner emits a charactersPresent list with no soft prior on ensemble size (solo / duo / trio+). If the corpus has a stable modal ensemble at chapter or beat granularity, that's a directional planner constraint.",
  "methodology": {
    "character_discovery": "Frequency-mined Title-Case tokens per book (>=10 mentions threshold), filtered against an excluded-set of place names, races, factions, weapons, and titles; cross-referenced with the project's known canon (Drizzt, Wulfgar, Bruenor, Catti-brie, Regis, Akar Kessell book 1, Artemis Entreri books 2-3, Pasha Pook book 3). Final per-book rosters: crystal_shard 21 chars, streams_of_silver 21, halflings_gem 22. Aliases (e.g., Drizzt <-> Do'Urden, Bruenor <-> Battlehammer, Regis <-> Rumblebelly) collapsed to canonical name.",
    "presence_threshold": "A character is 'present' in a scene/beat if their regex matches >=2 times in that segment. Threshold filters single-mention name-drops while preserving meaningfully on-page characters.",
    "ensemble_buckets": "empty (0 chars detected) / solo (1) / duo (2) / trio (3) / quad_plus (4+).",
    "granularity_caveat": "Streams of Silver has dramatically larger scene segmentation (median 952w/scene vs ~488-565w in the other two books); scene-level ensemble counts there mechanically include more characters per scene. Beat-level granularity is more uniform across books (median 107w/beat in all three) and is the more comparable signal."
  },
